WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.220
Okay, so I'm a big fan of CAR-T cell therapy, but I'm also a big fan of Bispecific.

00:00:08.220 --> 00:00:11.000
So why do we have to choose one or the other?

00:00:11.180 --> 00:00:20.080
So today I'll be talking about a trial that we have ongoing at MGB of L-renatumab, the

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:26.160
BCMA Bispecific, as a consolidation after Idacel.

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:33.120
So, you know, this is a question that's been brought up, you know, now, you know, is there

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:37.820
ever a situation to actually use Idacel over Siltacel for our myeloma patients?

00:00:39.220 --> 00:00:42.280
Well, reason one, maybe to enroll them onto this trial.

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:49.300
Reason number two, though, is, you know, there are select patients who are particularly risk

00:00:49.300 --> 00:00:55.340
adverse, and they can be concerned about that small risk of severe or irreversible toxicity

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:58.600
that can come with Siltacel in the form of non-ICANS

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:03.340
neurotoxicity, enterocolitis, and secondary hematologic malignancies.

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:12.200
And we want to make, so, you know, we have Idacel, we know it's not as efficacious as

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:17.000
Siltacel, but so what are strategies that we can use to improve CAR-T cell efficacy?

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:22.940
Well, you can make new, better CAR-T cells, and we have other CAR-T cells in the pipeline,

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:25.460
but, you know, we can't wait forever.

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:28.060
You could think about adjunct therapies.

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:33.340
During the CAR-T cell process, or you can think about consolidation or maintenance

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:34.980
approaches after CAR-T.

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:38.620
And so that's where we're going to focus as a consolidation after CAR-T.

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:45.300
We know for Idacel, like many other therapies, the depth of response correlates with the

00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:46.240
duration of response.

00:01:46.540 --> 00:01:51.540
So in the CARMA studies, you know, patients who actually got a CR, a stringent CR after

00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:56.460
Idacel, their median PFS was 19 months, which is, you know, much higher than the median

00:01:56.460 --> 00:01:56.940
PFS.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:01:59.000
Of 13 months.

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:06.020
And, you know, biospecific antibodies, you know, are almost a common sense partner as

00:02:06.020 --> 00:02:07.520
consolidation after CAR-T cells.

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:09.860
They have very complementary mechanisms of action.

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:15.700
So the idea here is that, you know, you could harness the activity of the CAR-T cells that

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:22.000
are also, that are already there, or you can induce polyclonal T cell expansion to deepen

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:22.740
the response.

00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:27.240
And that's kind of the principle, the concept behind the epigenetic response.

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:27.340
And that's kind of the principle, the concept behind the epigenetic response.

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:27.340
And that's kind of the principle, the concept behind the epigenetic response.

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:35.480
Here, the biospecific antibodies are trying to reinvigorate that polyclonal T cell expansion

00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:38.920
and improve the CAR-T cell persistence that's there.

00:02:39.940 --> 00:02:44.600
And then rather than giving it as a continuous kind of maintenance approach, here we're using

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:50.500
a fixed duration consolidation approach to avoid overtreatment, to prevent T cell exhaustion,

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:55.360
and to really, you know, you know, promote that principle of one and done or extended

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:56.720
time off therapy.

00:02:56.880 --> 00:02:57.340
That would be the principle.

00:02:57.340 --> 00:03:27.320
And then rather than giving it as a continuous kind of maintenance approach to avoid overtreatment,

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:34.100
most patients are getting, starting ELRA at about three months after IDASEL.

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:36.560
And it's six cycles of ELRA.

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:41.600
So the first two cycles are weekly, and then the four, the four following cycles are every

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:44.900
two weeks, primary endpoint progression-free survival.

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:50.260
And we allow patients to do the ELRA step-up dosing as an outpatient or as an inpatient.

00:03:53.100 --> 00:03:57.300
So, so far, we've, you know, as our last data cut, you know, 20% of patients have been

00:03:57.300 --> 00:03:57.320
tested.

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:00.860
So we've had about 20 patients had started ELRA consolidation, and about half of them

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:03.680
actually got their step-up dosing as an outpatient.

00:04:04.300 --> 00:04:07.000
They started about three months after IDASEL.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:13.100
And 13 patients have completed the ELRA treatment, and 17 patients were still having ongoing

00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:13.820
treatment.

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:17.800
All right, so these are the patient characteristics.

00:04:18.060 --> 00:04:20.080
Just a few things that I wanted to point out.

00:04:20.580 --> 00:04:24.000
You know, about a third of the patients were 75 years or older.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:25.980
So this is an older patient population.

00:04:26.820 --> 00:04:29.100
The median prior lines of therapy is, you know, three.

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:35.080
So seems like a less heavily pretreated patient population, generally earlier line.

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:39.860
The majority of the patients, 85% received bridging therapy.

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:47.400
And almost half of the patients only had a partial response or stable disease after IDASEL.

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:51.700
This is our swimmer's plot.

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:53.840
So we have 19 evaluable patients here.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:56.600
And, you know,

00:04:56.800 --> 00:05:05.160
I just want to point out that we do have patients who are, you know, having durable responses after IDASEL, after ELRA.

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:10.360
So five patients have had an ongoing CR at 12 months after starting ELRA.

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:15.620
There's three patients here who have had an ongoing CR at 18 months after starting ELRA.

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:19.320
So that's basically like 21 months after IDASEL.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:26.280
We've only had, of these 19 patients, only one patient has had progressive disease, which occurred about,

00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:28.740
11 months from IDASEL.

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:37.680
And this patient actually, interestingly, only had a small subcutaneous plasmacytoma, which was excised.

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:42.860
They got localized local radiation therapy to the plasmacytoma site.

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:48.620
And then since then has actually remained off systemic therapy without further progression,

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:56.780
extramedullary or biochemically, and an MRD negative stringency are upwards to 22 months from,

00:05:56.780 --> 00:05:57.620
their IDASEL.

00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:04.960
And we see deepening of the CR rates of the response.

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:13.900
So of the 11 patients who started ELRA and VGPR or less, 82% had deepening of their response.

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:23.260
The MRD data is still premature, but among the three evaluable patients who had MRD positive disease at baseline,

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:26.040
and then evaluable MRD after,

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:30.260
completing ELRA, all had conversion to MRD negativity.

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:35.340
And of the evaluable patients, none have lost MRD negativity.

00:06:35.340 --> 00:06:41.340
So the patients who went in MRD negative, they've remained MRD negative even six months post IDASEL.

00:06:44.940 --> 00:06:52.600
So safety, you know, we see pretty low rates of CRS, 35% of patients had grade one CRS.

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:55.180
There was one patient at grade two CRS.

00:06:55.540 --> 00:06:56.740
We don't see any ICANN.

00:06:56.740 --> 00:06:59.720
And we don't see any, we haven't had any high grade CRS.

00:07:00.580 --> 00:07:07.920
We do see hematologic toxicity in the forms of grade three, four neutropenia and 45% of the patients.

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:13.840
The big thing that we were really cognizant of is the infection risk.

00:07:14.020 --> 00:07:20.560
So these are patients who have just gotten a BCMA targeted CAR-T cell therapy, and we're giving them a BCMA Bispecific.

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:26.720
So this is, you know, one thing that we're really watching closely, 65% of patients have had infections.

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:31.940
But only three patients or 15% have had grade three infections.

00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:36.000
We've had one patient come off study because of infections.

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:41.140
He had disseminated VZV followed by cholecystitis, and she stopped ALRA.

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:51.120
20% of the patients have had CMV reactivation, but none required starting CMV directed treatment.

00:07:52.260 --> 00:07:56.180
And 75% of the patients were getting IVIG repletion.

00:07:56.180 --> 00:08:02.460
And now we're, it was recommended in the initial protocol, and now we've kind of like mandated it in an amendment.

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:07.580
So, you know, this is the conclusion.

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:09.900
The concept is viable.

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:11.860
You know, we can do fixed duration consolidation.

00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:18.820
We're seeing deepening of responses, and we're seeing only like a moderate infection risk.

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:22.840
Obviously, we need longer follow up to see what the PFS is.

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:26.060
Is this better than, you know, if you were to do them sequentially, you know.

00:08:26.180 --> 00:08:28.700
It's not a randomized trial, but that's kind of what we want to see.

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:37.300
And we're doing a lot of correlative work to look at the T cell dynamics in this consolidation strategy.

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:41.240
So this is, I just want to thank all of our huge team.
